  "doc_id": "33666",
  "text": "Th e use of the Clapeyron equation too has its limitations near saturation. It has been argued that the soil water freezing curve as calculated using the Clapeyron equation only resembles the soil water retention curve in unfrozen soil when the soil water is held by adsorptive forces and not by capillary forces [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Th is implies that the Clapeyron equation should only be applied in the dry region of the water retention curve where adsorption dominates. In the wet range, where capillary water is prominent, complicated corrections would be needed to account for the presence of both air-water and ice-water interfaces in the capillaries, which have diff erent surface tensions [CITATION_4] .",
